Phase 1 — Problem & Data
    •    Goal: Predict cardio from lifestyle/vitals.
    •    Train/holdout split: Stratified 80/20 (or 70/30) with a fixed random seed.

Phase 2 — EDA (Exploratory Data Analysis)
    •    Convert age (days → years), compute BMI, pulse pressure (ap_hi - ap_lo).
    •    Check distributions, missingness (usually minimal here), and crazy outliers (e.g., diastolic > systolic, ap_hi > 250, ap_lo < 40).
    •    Simple visuals: histograms, boxplots, pairwise correlations, target vs. key features.

Phase 3 — Cleaning & Feature Prep
    •    Outlier rules (document them): e.g., keep ap_hi ∈ [80, 240], ap_lo ∈ [40, 140], and ap_hi > ap_lo.
    •    Encode categoricals (gender, cholesterol, gluc) → one-hot or ordinal as appropriate.
    •    Scaling (only if using linear/SVM): StandardScaler for numeric columns.

Phase 4 — Baselines
    •    DummyClassifier (majority) → sanity check.
    •    Logistic Regression (with/without scaling) → interpretable baseline.
    •    Record: Accuracy, F1, ROC-AUC, PR-AUC (PR-AUC is helpful if mild imbalance).

Phase 5 — Stronger Models
    •    Random Forest and Gradient Boosted Trees (e.g., XGBoost/LightGBM).
    •    5-fold stratified CV on train set; simple hyperparameter search (max_depth, n_estimators, learning_rate).
    •    Compare on the held-out test set (don’t peek earlier).
Phase 6 — Interpretation
    •    Feature importance (gain/SHAP for tree models; coefficients for LR).
    •    Partial dependence or simple ICE on top 2–3 features (optional).
    •    Calibration plot (reliability curve) to show probability quality (optional).

Phase 7 — Robustness & Ethics (short but strong)
    •    Check class balance after cleaning; report if you used class_weight='balanced'.
    •    Brief note on bias (e.g., male/female performance).
    •    Limitations (self-reported lifestyle, single snapshot, not medical advice).

Phase 8 — Deliverables
    •    4–6 plots: EDA (2), ROC/PR curves, confusion matrix, feature importance, calibration (optional).
    •    Paper (6–8 pages): problem, data, methods, results, interpretation, limits.
    •    Clean notebook with narrative + requirements.txt.